143
00:07:32,113 --> 00:07:33,374
Game one, slightly better.

144
00:07:33,834 --> 00:07:35,815
They have similar lifetime buyer percentage.

145
00:07:36,335 --> 00:07:37,696
Game two, it's slightly higher.

146
00:07:38,096 --> 00:07:40,837
You can see from this chart that their daily ARPU,

147
00:07:40,997 --> 00:07:44,039
average revenue per paying user, is also very similar.

148
00:07:45,159 --> 00:07:48,481
Since ARPU, average revenue per user, is just.

149
00:07:49,442 --> 00:07:53,264
Buyer conversion times ARPU, they should have the same

150
00:07:53,324 --> 00:07:54,024
numbers, right?

151
00:07:54,765 --> 00:07:56,245
But of course you know that I'm setting you up.

152
00:07:59,447 --> 00:08:05,150
So game one has an ARPU of $2.27, and game two has an

153
00:08:05,210 --> 00:08:08,411
ARPU of only $0.84, even though those other numbers

154
00:08:08,431 --> 00:08:09,232
looked really similar.

155
00:08:09,792 --> 00:08:12,733
And the reason is because people are playing game one

156
00:08:12,893 --> 00:08:14,154
much longer than game two.

157
00:08:14,675 --> 00:08:16,857
and it has many more transactions per buyer.

158
00:08:17,338 --> 00:08:20,281
So D30 is higher, transactions per buyer,

159
00:08:20,481 --> 00:08:22,624
and its lifetime ARPAPU is much higher.

160
00:08:22,644 --> 00:08:26,128
And if you only looked at daily statistics,

161
00:08:26,428 --> 00:08:29,011
you wouldn't realize quite how different these games are.

162
00:08:30,746 --> 00:08:33,887
So one way to think of yourself is as a detective.

163
00:08:34,307 --> 00:08:37,128
The witnesses may be lying or confused.

164
00:08:37,468 --> 00:08:38,969
The crime scene may have been tampered with.

165
00:08:39,309 --> 00:08:41,549
You can't trust any one piece of evidence

166
00:08:41,669 --> 00:08:43,490
and you need to constantly cross-check them

167
00:08:43,850 --> 00:08:46,471
against each other to validate what you're finding out.

168
00:08:48,093 --> 00:08:50,854
So we do a lot of triangulating in truth,

169
00:08:50,994 --> 00:08:54,296
and we do it by taking every source of data that we have

170
00:08:54,456 --> 00:08:57,357
and comparing against each other almost all the time.

171
00:08:57,497 --> 00:09:00,218
So we've got client data from the Congregate SDK.

172
00:09:00,638 --> 00:09:04,679
We compare it to Adjust, which is our mobile attribution

173
00:09:05,439 --> 00:09:07,940
provider that's also firing in our client.

174
00:09:08,200 --> 00:09:09,541
We compare it to our server data.

175
00:09:09,881 --> 00:09:13,723
We compare it to data from the platforms, and then we compare it to benchmarks that

176
00:09:13,743 --> 00:09:15,083
we've built up over the years.

177
00:09:15,584 --> 00:09:18,505
Because there's always some variance between sources of data.

178
00:09:18,765 --> 00:09:24,828
Sometimes it's 1%, some things could be as much as 5%, and that could be normal and tolerable.

179
00:09:25,088 --> 00:09:26,909
But you need to understand what that is.

180
00:09:27,029 --> 00:09:29,750
So we track everything all the time.

181
00:09:29,810 --> 00:09:33,632
This is from some dashboards that we have where we're comparing four different pieces

182
00:09:33,672 --> 00:09:36,213
of data next to each other and tracking that.

183
00:09:36,724 --> 00:09:39,145
And then we track the variance over time

184
00:09:39,205 --> 00:09:42,047
so that we have a ceiling and a floor that's acceptable.

185
00:09:42,387 --> 00:09:44,728
And anything beyond that, we look beyond.

186
00:09:45,548 --> 00:09:47,349
We check into it and make sure that it's correct.

187
00:09:49,210 --> 00:09:50,251
And you're not just a detective.

188
00:09:50,291 --> 00:09:51,871
You're a CSI.

189
00:09:52,652 --> 00:09:55,613
Your goal should be to create a three-dimensional view

190
00:09:56,394 --> 00:09:58,895
of your players and how they're moving through your game.

191
00:10:00,416 --> 00:10:03,997
Games are very complex and time-based systems.

192
00:10:04,318 --> 00:10:06,018
And a flat view is never going to be enough.

193
00:10:08,263 --> 00:10:10,785
Another way to think about this, and this comes from,

194
00:10:10,805 --> 00:10:13,886
I should really not press against my chest.

195
00:10:15,407 --> 00:10:17,088
My favorite, while I majored in

196
00:10:17,248 --> 00:10:18,849
Russian Eastern European Studies,

197
00:10:18,969 --> 00:10:21,230
my favorite class in college was actually

198
00:10:21,330 --> 00:10:23,071
astrophysics for non-science majors.

199
00:10:23,511 --> 00:10:26,352
And I think there's a lot to learn from astrophysics

200
00:10:26,412 --> 00:10:27,893
to help us think about how we should be

201
00:10:27,933 --> 00:10:30,574
building up data for games.

202
00:10:30,974 --> 00:10:32,495
So if you think about the universe,

203
00:10:33,490 --> 00:10:36,792
We're sitting in one spot on planet Earth.

204
00:10:37,333 --> 00:10:38,953
And that's a really limited view.

205
00:10:39,053 --> 00:10:41,615
And we have really limited tools to understand what this

206
00:10:41,675 --> 00:10:42,876
enormous thing is doing.

207
00:10:43,356 --> 00:10:46,398
And for years, millennia, we didn't really understand it.

208
00:10:47,038 --> 00:10:50,520
But gradually, through first our visual observations with

209
00:10:50,580 --> 00:10:54,082
our eyes, and then by building more and more tools, and

210
00:10:54,122 --> 00:10:56,363
taking more and more observations from different

211
00:10:56,403 --> 00:10:59,905
places, and then comparing those observations against

212
00:10:59,965 --> 00:11:00,365
each other.

213
00:11:00,782 --> 00:11:04,165
we've been able to build up a really beautiful and impressive

214
00:11:04,245 --> 00:11:06,808
model of the universe, a 3D model,

215
00:11:06,888 --> 00:11:08,209
and how everything works together.

216
00:11:08,610 --> 00:11:09,951
Is everything accurate yet?

217
00:11:10,832 --> 00:11:11,172
It isn't.

218
00:11:11,753 --> 00:11:12,594
It absolutely isn't.

219
00:11:12,674 --> 00:11:15,757
But when you think about 2,000 years ago when

220
00:11:15,777 --> 00:11:19,621
we thought that the sun revolved around the Earth,

221
00:11:19,721 --> 00:11:22,083
it's really amazing how far we've been able to come.

222
00:11:24,333 --> 00:11:26,314
I want to talk about a lot of mistakes.

223
00:11:26,934 --> 00:11:29,456
There's a series of classic data mistakes

224
00:11:29,496 --> 00:11:30,656
that almost everybody makes.

225
00:11:31,257 --> 00:11:33,018
I make them, even though I fight against them.

226
00:11:33,458 --> 00:11:37,180
So I wanted to take everybody through some examples

227
00:11:37,440 --> 00:11:41,763
of how they happen and what to watch out for.

228
00:11:43,529 --> 00:11:46,390
And the first one and the first thing that you should

229
00:11:46,450 --> 00:11:48,430
always be thinking about whenever you look at numbers

230
00:11:48,750 --> 00:11:49,870
is audience mix.

231
00:11:50,471 --> 00:11:55,592
So we tend to think of our player bases as monolithic,

232
00:11:56,332 --> 00:11:58,812
one individual millions of times.

233
00:11:59,192 --> 00:12:01,573
But that's not really the way to think about it.

234
00:12:01,733 --> 00:12:05,314
It's really an aggregation of all kinds of subgroups of

235
00:12:05,374 --> 00:12:08,534
people from different demographics, who've been in

236
00:12:08,574 --> 00:12:10,735
the game different amount of times, who came from different

237
00:12:10,795 --> 00:12:12,835
sources, who are playing on different devices.

238
00:12:13,376 --> 00:12:18,362
And how those subgroups mingle and how they mix

239
00:12:18,903 --> 00:12:21,005
have a huge effect on our KPIs.

240
00:12:21,626 --> 00:12:24,029
Usually when KPIs for a game change,

241
00:12:24,289 --> 00:12:27,193
it's more often because the mix of the audience has changed

242
00:12:27,453 --> 00:12:29,836
than that the game itself has actually changed.

