506
00:26:11,757 --> 00:26:14,418
In particular, in games, the curse that we need

507
00:26:14,438 --> 00:26:16,598
to watch out for is that absolutely everything

508
00:26:16,658 --> 00:26:17,819
correlates with engagement.

509
00:26:18,699 --> 00:26:20,739
And sometimes that's meaningful, but usually,

510
00:26:21,761 --> 00:26:22,161
It isn't.

511
00:26:23,322 --> 00:26:26,264
A classic example that I've seen is people saying,

512
00:26:26,684 --> 00:26:29,245
players who connect to Facebook are twice as valuable

513
00:26:30,106 --> 00:26:33,708
as everybody else, so we should incentivize

514
00:26:34,308 --> 00:26:35,969
Facebook connections because then they'll be better.

515
00:26:36,849 --> 00:26:39,131
Maybe that's true, but more likely it's that

516
00:26:39,511 --> 00:26:42,693
engaged players were the ones who were willing

517
00:26:42,713 --> 00:26:44,574
to take the risk that they're gonna spam their friends

518
00:26:44,754 --> 00:26:46,395
and make the connection.

519
00:26:48,617 --> 00:26:53,380
So the true way to separate causation and correlation,

520
00:26:53,400 --> 00:26:57,183
or correlation causation, figure out what's really happening

521
00:26:57,864 --> 00:27:01,747
is A-B tests, and those are really powerful.

522
00:27:03,416 --> 00:27:08,041
It's not a magic bullet because nothing in data is that easy.

523
00:27:08,781 --> 00:27:09,902
Testing has real costs.

524
00:27:10,723 --> 00:27:16,929
Engineering time, overhead, complexity, confusing players,

525
00:27:17,009 --> 00:27:19,151
divisions between your players.

526
00:27:19,632 --> 00:27:22,414
And the more tests that you're running, the worse that gets.

527
00:27:24,172 --> 00:27:28,635
In general, the test traps within A-B tests are a lot of

528
00:27:28,655 --> 00:27:30,556
the things that I've been talking about, like sample

529
00:27:30,596 --> 00:27:34,318
sizes, audience mix, cherry picking, confirmation bias,

530
00:27:34,518 --> 00:27:35,519
power distributions.

531
00:27:35,919 --> 00:27:38,721
But there are a few additional test traps that you need to

532
00:27:39,061 --> 00:27:42,263
watch out for, mostly having to do with assignment.

533
00:27:43,704 --> 00:27:46,866
So one thing when you're doing test assignments to keep in

534
00:27:46,926 --> 00:27:48,887
mind is that it's important to make sure.

535
00:27:49,299 --> 00:27:52,040
that you split your test on what you're actually testing on.

536
00:27:52,520 --> 00:27:55,681
So example here is a test in the store.

537
00:27:56,281 --> 00:27:58,942
One way to assign people to the test is whenever they show up

538
00:27:58,982 --> 00:28:04,103
in the app, they go in group A or group B. And then later,

539
00:28:04,164 --> 00:28:07,264
maybe, they will engage with the store,

540
00:28:07,304 --> 00:28:08,805
and you'll see the results.

541
00:28:09,245 --> 00:28:12,446
The problem with that is that you could very easily end up

542
00:28:12,586 --> 00:28:15,327
with a unequal distribution of people

543
00:28:15,387 --> 00:28:16,507
who interact with the store.

544
00:28:16,991 --> 00:28:21,475
And therefore, your test is biased by something that has

545
00:28:21,515 --> 00:28:24,377
nothing to do with the thing you're actually testing.

546
00:28:24,817 --> 00:28:26,899
The other thing is that if you're looking at multiple

547
00:28:26,939 --> 00:28:29,721
metrics, like retention or anything like that, then the

548
00:28:29,801 --> 00:28:32,943
noise from the people involved in the test may be drowned out

549
00:28:33,003 --> 00:28:34,064
by the larger sample.

550
00:28:34,325 --> 00:28:38,768
So always split once people have engaged with whatever

551
00:28:38,788 --> 00:28:39,288
you're testing.

552
00:28:41,650 --> 00:28:48,193
The even bigger assignment problem in tests has to do with time and anything we do to

553
00:28:48,213 --> 00:28:51,975
adjust when people are assigned to tests.

554
00:28:52,055 --> 00:28:56,477
So revenue is a power distribution, so is engagement.

555
00:28:56,757 --> 00:29:01,818
your best players always show up first, they always show up earliest, they show up oftenest.

556
00:29:02,258 --> 00:29:05,799
And so if you only run a test for one day,

557
00:29:06,200 --> 00:29:10,201
then your sample is going to be heavily biased towards your best players.

558
00:29:10,581 --> 00:29:14,782
If you run it for longer, then you'll get a lot of less engaged players who come back,

559
00:29:14,862 --> 00:29:16,343
and you'll get a more normal sample.

560
00:29:16,989 --> 00:29:19,110
in terms of what your player base looks like.

561
00:29:19,670 --> 00:29:22,711
Similarly, if you have heard of people doing, you know,

562
00:29:22,751 --> 00:29:25,673
tests, assigning people based on one day, next day,

563
00:29:25,813 --> 00:29:28,774
one day, next day, again, you're going to get

564
00:29:28,794 --> 00:29:30,855
a very biased sample that way.

565
00:29:31,436 --> 00:29:33,517
Now, there's cases where you may want,

566
00:29:34,077 --> 00:29:36,018
you may be forced into it from,

567
00:29:36,198 --> 00:29:38,379
like if you want to test a store on Steam

568
00:29:38,419 --> 00:29:40,260
or some other place that doesn't give you tools,

569
00:29:40,820 --> 00:29:42,361
but even there you want to be very careful.

570
00:29:42,780 --> 00:29:45,462
because people who show up on Tuesday may not be the same

571
00:29:45,502 --> 00:29:46,863
people who show up on Saturday.

572
00:29:47,063 --> 00:29:50,066
So you want to do things that create an equal sample and an

573
00:29:50,606 --> 00:29:58,292
equal type of person interacting with the test.

574
00:29:58,852 --> 00:30:01,454
Another thing to keep in mind is downstream impacts.

575
00:30:01,854 --> 00:30:05,877
A lot of commercial A-B test products will make you pick

576
00:30:05,897 --> 00:30:06,498
just one.

577
00:30:08,894 --> 00:30:12,420
one KPI that you're testing and that they're gonna,

578
00:30:12,860 --> 00:30:14,363
you're supposed to just judge the test

579
00:30:14,583 --> 00:30:18,028
on that particular metric and decide which is the winner.

580
00:30:19,328 --> 00:30:22,730
They do that because they want to stop you from fishing for a

581
00:30:22,750 --> 00:30:28,073
particular result and cherry picking, oh, this was good, so

582
00:30:28,093 --> 00:30:33,295
A, and I wanted B to win, and this is good on B, so B is the

583
00:30:33,335 --> 00:30:33,576
winner.

584
00:30:34,036 --> 00:30:38,418
And that kind of fishing is bad, but what we've seen is

585
00:30:38,438 --> 00:30:41,099
that there's so many unintended consequences to

586
00:30:41,139 --> 00:30:41,720
different tests.

587
00:30:42,053 --> 00:30:44,376
that it's always better to look at the full picture

588
00:30:44,777 --> 00:30:47,080
and look at everything that happened

589
00:30:47,361 --> 00:30:50,626
and then make a decision based on the full picture

590
00:30:51,347 --> 00:30:53,069
as to whether the test was a success or not.

591
00:30:54,198 --> 00:30:57,540
So an example, the screenshots you saw earlier of the store

592
00:30:57,580 --> 00:31:00,581
test were a test that we ran recently on one of our games

593
00:31:00,901 --> 00:31:03,381
that is a very complicated store with a lot of items.

594
00:31:03,481 --> 00:31:07,523
And we had a theory that the number of items and how

595
00:31:07,583 --> 00:31:11,224
complicated it was was confusing players and reducing

596
00:31:11,244 --> 00:31:14,485
a number of people who were actually buying items.

597
00:31:14,625 --> 00:31:18,566
So we did a simpler version of the store that focused on just

598
00:31:18,606 --> 00:31:19,247
a few items.

599
00:31:20,004 --> 00:31:21,766
and tested them against each other.

600
00:31:21,866 --> 00:31:24,448
So the main thing that we were looking for

601
00:31:24,488 --> 00:31:26,209
was to see an increase in conversion.

602
00:31:27,250 --> 00:31:30,332
And great, we increased it.

603
00:31:30,712 --> 00:31:33,374
We increased the conversion with the simplified store by 9%.

604
00:31:34,055 --> 00:31:37,757
The problem is that by removing some of the items,

605
00:31:37,818 --> 00:31:43,662
we removed some of the items that the most engaged players

606
00:31:43,722 --> 00:31:44,442
were spending on.

607
00:31:44,843 --> 00:31:47,405
So even though we increased conversion,

608
00:31:47,889 --> 00:31:51,573
The average revenue per paying user dropped drastically, and

609
00:31:52,615 --> 00:31:53,816
overall revenue was down 11%.

610
00:31:54,857 --> 00:31:59,824
So conversion up, revenue down, oops, that was maybe not

611
00:32:00,064 --> 00:32:01,085
the greatest thing to have done.

612
00:32:01,205 --> 00:32:03,749
So we reverted to the control and are

613
00:32:03,889 --> 00:32:04,950
continuing to experiment.

614
00:32:07,017 --> 00:32:13,063
Along with not looking, another flaw that you can get into with A-B tests is looking

615
00:32:13,083 --> 00:32:14,604
at results too early.

616
00:32:15,145 --> 00:32:19,829
So here's another example from our game Office Space where we did some, this is from a little

617
00:32:19,869 --> 00:32:24,713
while back where we did, we were testing kind of a flash sale for individual items.

618
00:32:26,875 --> 00:32:33,621
They popped in, and certain players, they would pop in, great deal, short-term discount.

619
00:32:34,683 --> 00:32:37,285
And you would expect it to increase conversion and reduce

620
00:32:37,305 --> 00:32:39,566
the ARPAPU and hopefully increase revenue.

621
00:32:39,886 --> 00:32:42,428
And when we looked at the test after running it for 10 days,

622
00:32:42,828 --> 00:32:44,149
that was exactly what we saw.

623
00:32:44,669 --> 00:32:47,511
Big increase in conversion, small decrease in ARPAPU, 8%

624
00:32:48,432 --> 00:32:51,914
increase in average revenue per user.

625
00:32:51,934 --> 00:32:51,994
Yay.

626
00:32:52,914 --> 00:32:58,218
But since these are all the bad cases, when we let the test

627
00:32:58,258 --> 00:33:00,880
run for 30 days and looked at the data again.

628
00:33:01,460 --> 00:33:05,263
The basic pattern of increased conversion and lower ARPAPU

629
00:33:05,283 --> 00:33:09,165
was still there, but everything had moved downwards to the

630
00:33:09,205 --> 00:33:12,368
point where we were now at a negative on revenue.

631
00:33:12,808 --> 00:33:15,990
Revenue had decreased by 2% because the long-term effect

632
00:33:16,350 --> 00:33:19,352
on average revenue per paying user was so much larger than

633
00:33:19,452 --> 00:33:20,153
on conversion.

634
00:33:23,067 --> 00:33:27,808
And part of the reason why that's important is because of

635
00:33:27,848 --> 00:33:30,849
statistical significance and the question of what's a big

636
00:33:31,169 --> 00:33:32,090
enough sample size?

637
00:33:32,690 --> 00:33:34,931
I have a particular point of view on this, which is that

638
00:33:36,511 --> 00:33:40,172
you don't want just the minimum number of players in a

639
00:33:40,332 --> 00:33:41,073
particular test.

640
00:33:41,513 --> 00:33:44,154
You don't want just enough to pass the statistical

641
00:33:44,194 --> 00:33:44,914
significance test.

642
00:33:45,174 --> 00:33:46,935
You want really big sample sizes.

643
00:33:47,455 --> 00:33:50,276
And this comes from, I think, from

644
00:33:51,101 --> 00:33:55,764
a misinterpretation that I think most people have on how statistical significance works.

645
00:33:56,325 --> 00:34:00,047
And I'm going to stumble over statistical significance a bunch of times because it's

646
00:34:00,107 --> 00:34:00,728
really hard to say.

647
00:34:01,588 --> 00:34:03,510
And it's really hard to say fast.

648
00:34:03,730 --> 00:34:08,893
So you'll hear things, people will say things like, we had a statistically significant 5%

649
00:34:10,074 --> 00:34:10,935
lift from this test.

650
00:34:13,036 --> 00:34:15,478
But that's not how statistical significance works.

651
00:34:18,139 --> 00:34:22,160
So the way statistical significance works is it

652
00:34:22,500 --> 00:34:26,121
assumes that there's a true underlying lift between the

653
00:34:26,161 --> 00:34:27,002
two populations.

654
00:34:27,822 --> 00:34:30,583
And that if you run the test again and again and again, the

655
00:34:32,323 --> 00:34:37,325
results will come back in a normal curve of results where

656
00:34:37,345 --> 00:34:40,506
the true mean is the underlying lift.

657
00:34:40,586 --> 00:34:43,547
So if you run a test, it passes the statistical

658
00:34:43,567 --> 00:34:44,567
significance, it's 5%.

659
00:34:46,230 --> 00:34:47,890
It could be from around the mean.

660
00:34:48,310 --> 00:34:51,691
It's probably a 40, 45% chance that it's in that range.

661
00:34:52,111 --> 00:34:56,132
But it also could come from the other part of the curve.

662
00:34:56,432 --> 00:34:59,332
In this case, 5%, the underlying lift

663
00:34:59,392 --> 00:35:00,333
would be something like 10%.

664
00:35:01,453 --> 00:35:04,273
Or it could come from the far upper end of the curve,

665
00:35:04,553 --> 00:35:07,514
in which case there might only be a 1% or 2% lift.

666
00:35:07,994 --> 00:35:09,514
And that's important in terms of how

667
00:35:09,554 --> 00:35:12,595
you think about what statistical significance means when

668
00:35:12,615 --> 00:35:13,695
you're looking at results.

669
00:35:14,962 --> 00:35:17,924
And this is why I really like large sample sizes,

670
00:35:18,044 --> 00:35:21,666
because if you have sort of double the sample size

671
00:35:21,746 --> 00:35:24,468
that you need, then it's like you've run the test twice

672
00:35:24,588 --> 00:35:25,669
and averaged the results.

673
00:35:26,069 --> 00:35:28,891
And over time, the results there are

674
00:35:28,911 --> 00:35:31,313
going to come closer and closer to that mean.

675
00:35:31,393 --> 00:35:34,215
So big test sizes whenever possible.

676
00:35:34,616 --> 00:35:37,438
But there are costs to that, so there's always trade-offs.

677
00:35:38,275 --> 00:35:40,256
Now, you know that I think this is a lie.

678
00:35:40,956 --> 00:35:45,178
So I want to talk about abnormal testing, because a

679
00:35:45,958 --> 00:35:48,859
lot of what we're looking at are engagement-related metrics

680
00:35:49,139 --> 00:35:52,400
or revenue-related metrics that are power distributions,

681
00:35:52,820 --> 00:35:54,341
and those need to be looked at differently.

682
00:35:54,761 --> 00:35:59,662
So this is our old friend, the power curve of revenue with

683
00:35:59,842 --> 00:36:00,583
buyers who spent $45,000, $50,000.

684
00:36:03,391 --> 00:36:06,773
If you think about what that means, here's a sample of a

685
00:36:06,974 --> 00:36:08,354
potential distribution in a game.

686
00:36:08,775 --> 00:36:11,476
It's not uncommon in free-to-play games to have 70

687
00:36:12,577 --> 00:36:15,279
or even 80% of revenue come from a very small percent of

688
00:36:15,339 --> 00:36:16,440
buyers who spent more than $500.

689
00:36:16,640 --> 00:36:22,824
These two A-B tests have exactly the same distribution,

690
00:36:23,004 --> 00:36:24,905
except for one has a $1,000 buyer and one has a $500 buyer.

691
00:36:27,647 --> 00:36:37,375
And the net impact of that is, in this small sample, a negative 40% on the average revenue per user,

692
00:36:37,696 --> 00:36:40,758
even though the distribution isn't very significant.

693
00:36:41,699 --> 00:36:46,203
That still happens when you have a larger test, and that's something that you need to...

694
00:36:46,849 --> 00:36:49,029
really need to look out for and watch out for,

695
00:36:49,309 --> 00:36:52,250
because a few big spenders can have a very big impact.

696
00:36:52,890 --> 00:36:53,810
How do you deal with that?

697
00:36:54,451 --> 00:36:56,451
It's really important to look at medians

698
00:36:56,611 --> 00:37:00,632
and any kind of distribution of how revenue

699
00:37:00,672 --> 00:37:01,873
and other things are coming in.

700
00:37:02,533 --> 00:37:04,553
So that previous example,

701
00:37:05,434 --> 00:37:08,674
the average was drastically different,

702
00:37:08,955 --> 00:37:10,475
but if you look at the medians, they're both 15.

703
00:37:11,335 --> 00:37:13,796
And that helps show you as an analyst that,

704
00:37:15,337 --> 00:37:19,638
the differences are happening just way at the top and not through the whole distribution.

705
00:37:20,579 --> 00:37:25,861
Another made-up example is this one where there's actually a big difference in the distribution.

706
00:37:26,161 --> 00:37:32,464
Everything is doubled on the second one, but has a slightly lower top buyer,

707
00:37:32,864 --> 00:37:34,825
and so the averages are very similar.

708
00:37:35,065 --> 00:37:38,387
But if you look at the median, it's double the other one,

709
00:37:38,647 --> 00:37:42,809
and that shows that probably that's the better outcome of the test.

710
00:37:43,228 --> 00:37:43,989
versus the other.

711
00:37:44,849 --> 00:37:47,590
So that simple store test that I talked about before, where

712
00:37:47,650 --> 00:37:49,331
we were looking at revenue, and that was what we were

713
00:37:49,351 --> 00:37:55,553
judging on, this chart helped us figure out what was going

714
00:37:55,753 --> 00:37:59,055
on, so this chart breaks out all the different purchase

715
00:37:59,075 --> 00:38:00,855
sizes and does it by day.

716
00:38:01,256 --> 00:38:04,017
And when we looked at the same chart for the simple store

717
00:38:04,097 --> 00:38:05,297
version versus the control.

718
00:38:05,767 --> 00:38:09,430
there was much less of that bright pink $100 purchases.

719
00:38:09,830 --> 00:38:12,532
So we were able to sort of confirm by looking at the

720
00:38:12,592 --> 00:38:14,753
distribution what had really happened.

721
00:38:15,474 --> 00:38:17,996
The other thing is that when you're looking at something

722
00:38:18,016 --> 00:38:22,999
like revenue or some kind of economy sink, instead of using

723
00:38:23,039 --> 00:38:27,082
a normal P or Z test, you should use something called a

724
00:38:27,162 --> 00:38:32,746
Wilcoxon Rank Sum Test, which compares the medians rather

725
00:38:32,806 --> 00:38:33,346
than the means.

726
00:38:34,160 --> 00:38:35,961
This isn't something that's easy to run by hand,

727
00:38:36,241 --> 00:38:38,282
but most statistical packages like R

728
00:38:38,622 --> 00:38:41,023
include it as an option, and that's what we use.

729
00:38:43,164 --> 00:38:44,885
Now I want to talk about testing's dirty secret,

730
00:38:45,305 --> 00:38:49,347
which is that most tests don't show a significant change.

731
00:38:49,807 --> 00:38:51,668
And this can be really frustrating for a team,

732
00:38:51,708 --> 00:38:53,468
because you've put a lot of work into creating

733
00:38:53,789 --> 00:38:55,549
two different versions of the game,

734
00:38:55,970 --> 00:38:59,411
and you want to have the work that you're doing have meaning.

735
00:38:59,471 --> 00:39:00,292
You want to have...

736
00:39:00,780 --> 00:39:01,881
You want to be improving things.

737
00:39:01,901 --> 00:39:03,242
You want to have numbers go up.

738
00:39:04,483 --> 00:39:06,304
But one of the things to remember

739
00:39:06,584 --> 00:39:10,788
is that a test that doesn't show a result

740
00:39:11,168 --> 00:39:12,889
is still meaningful and still interesting.

741
00:39:14,611 --> 00:39:18,534
Here's an example from Butterscotch Shenanigans,

742
00:39:18,574 --> 00:39:19,775
who made the game Crashlands.

743
00:39:20,435 --> 00:39:22,937
They were kind enough to share this particular example.

744
00:39:23,818 --> 00:39:28,121
They wrote for the game a huge, long, very detailed description.

745
00:39:29,982 --> 00:39:31,443
were wondering how much of an impact

746
00:39:31,483 --> 00:39:32,684
is that having on conversion?

747
00:39:33,004 --> 00:39:36,466
So they decided using Google's A-B testing tools

748
00:39:36,506 --> 00:39:39,828
and Android to test the most extreme possible version of that,

749
00:39:40,148 --> 00:39:41,708
which was no description at all,

750
00:39:42,009 --> 00:39:45,070
just their four or five accolades

751
00:39:45,410 --> 00:39:47,471
that were talking about how awesome a game it is.

752
00:39:49,192 --> 00:39:50,173
So they ran it for four months,

753
00:39:50,893 --> 00:39:53,435
and it shows absolutely zero difference

754
00:39:53,495 --> 00:39:55,836
between having this, like, thousand-word description.

755
00:39:56,413 --> 00:39:56,994
and zero.

756
00:39:57,654 --> 00:39:59,636
Now, on the one hand, that could be frustrating,

757
00:39:59,736 --> 00:40:02,379
all that work wasted on writing description,

758
00:40:02,779 --> 00:40:06,123
but in all game companies, in all companies really,

759
00:40:06,143 --> 00:40:08,845
a time and effort is really valuable.

760
00:40:09,146 --> 00:40:12,609
So anything that shows you what is not worth doing

761
00:40:12,789 --> 00:40:14,351
and what is not making a big difference

762
00:40:14,651 --> 00:40:16,493
is something that you can reduce your focus on.

763
00:40:17,432 --> 00:40:20,054
This result, where description has very little impact,

764
00:40:20,555 --> 00:40:23,337
is exactly what we've seen in terms of our testing using

765
00:40:23,357 --> 00:40:28,482
the A-B tool set that Google gives us, which is really nice.

766
00:40:29,162 --> 00:40:31,344
At the high end, icon has a big impact.

767
00:40:31,644 --> 00:40:32,905
Video has some impact.

768
00:40:33,306 --> 00:40:34,987
Screenshots, a little less.

769
00:40:35,027 --> 00:40:36,408
And then description, not too much.

770
00:40:36,909 --> 00:40:38,550
And overall, this kind of testing

771
00:40:38,590 --> 00:40:39,831
has been really useful for us.

772
00:40:40,212 --> 00:40:43,454
We used to spend a lot of time arguing about game names,

773
00:40:43,794 --> 00:40:46,416
but then we did a lot of A-B testing of game names

774
00:40:46,476 --> 00:40:48,758
against each other, never saw a difference in result,

775
00:40:49,038 --> 00:40:52,241
and now we're much, much chiller about choosing a game name.

776
00:40:52,681 --> 00:40:56,083
And yeah, so we can let some of those arguments

777
00:40:56,103 --> 00:40:58,505
die a little faster because we've had data that tells us

778
00:40:58,785 --> 00:40:59,806
this isn't that important.

779
00:41:01,587 --> 00:41:01,768
But.

780
00:41:02,458 --> 00:41:05,724
When you're testing, it's also very important not

781
00:41:05,784 --> 00:41:07,668
to extrapolate too much from the result.

782
00:41:08,449 --> 00:41:11,895
As you've heard, we're big fans of Google's A-B testing store

783
00:41:11,936 --> 00:41:12,817
tools on Android.

784
00:41:13,724 --> 00:41:16,487
were such big fans, they actually did a case study on

785
00:41:16,587 --> 00:41:21,532
our use of it and came to our offices and took a video of

786
00:41:21,672 --> 00:41:25,356
all of our bunch of employees talking about particular tests.

787
00:41:25,597 --> 00:41:28,980
Here's our senior producer, Peter Eichmann, talking about

788
00:41:29,020 --> 00:41:32,143
an A-B icon test we did for a game called Global Assault.

789
00:41:34,359 --> 00:41:39,029
And we had been using this girl with a gun icon as our main one

790
00:41:39,150 --> 00:41:40,873
and tested a helicopter against it

791
00:41:41,214 --> 00:41:42,878
and got a 92% increase in conversions.

792
00:41:45,795 --> 00:41:50,159
92% is a really big amount and had an impact of hundreds of thousands,

793
00:41:50,499 --> 00:41:53,301
probably millions of installs on the game.

794
00:41:53,782 --> 00:41:56,624
So really exciting, great, yay testing.

795
00:41:57,505 --> 00:41:58,506
Except for there's a funny thing.

796
00:41:59,287 --> 00:42:02,930
The reason that we were using that girl with a gun icon testing

797
00:42:03,370 --> 00:42:08,415
is because we had tested various different potential icons on Kongregate.com

798
00:42:09,315 --> 00:42:11,297
and that's the one that won.

799
00:42:11,397 --> 00:42:12,678
So the helicopter...

800
00:42:13,099 --> 00:42:18,003
So the girl with the gun had a 0.28% conversion rate on congregate and a 0.19%.

801
00:42:18,604 --> 00:42:20,085
The helicopter had a 0.19%.

802
00:42:20,766 --> 00:42:23,489
So the results were almost exactly flipped.

803
00:42:24,169 --> 00:42:28,654
And that's why you need to be really careful when you're testing to think about context

804
00:42:29,094 --> 00:42:34,860
and make sure that you repeat any test and that not everything is going to work the same

805
00:42:34,900 --> 00:42:37,523
way in the same place, in different places.

806
00:42:38,834 --> 00:42:42,317
Another thing to keep in mind is that not everything is testable.

807
00:42:43,158 --> 00:42:47,842
Specifically late game stuff, late game and late game players.

808
00:42:48,382 --> 00:42:49,623
It can be very difficult to test.

809
00:42:50,044 --> 00:42:55,228
This is a really nice quote from Daniel Cook of Spryfox and Lost Garden

810
00:42:55,248 --> 00:42:56,589
that I saw on Twitter recently.

811
00:42:57,150 --> 00:43:02,874
He was talking about YouTube and how the algorithm changes the audience.

812
00:43:02,954 --> 00:43:06,017
But I think that it's a really good way of thinking.

813
00:43:06,587 --> 00:43:10,548
of thinking about things, particularly that the game also changes the audience.

814
00:43:10,989 --> 00:43:14,430
The longer somebody is in the game, you're setting their expectations.

815
00:43:14,510 --> 00:43:17,311
You're training them to behave in a certain way.

816
00:43:17,651 --> 00:43:22,032
And the later you get in a game, they're not going to react to something the same way they

817
00:43:22,092 --> 00:43:24,893
might have on day one or day four and day eight.

818
00:43:25,993 --> 00:43:27,174
Players talk to each other.

819
00:43:27,554 --> 00:43:29,174
That makes it harder to test as well.

820
00:43:29,235 --> 00:43:33,256
So there's a lot of things happening at the end of a game that make it difficult to test.

821
00:43:34,499 --> 00:43:38,103
So I've created, because I like frameworks, my hierarchy

822
00:43:38,143 --> 00:43:40,326
of testing from critical to difficult.

823
00:43:40,566 --> 00:43:43,971
And it basically follows the funnel of players into a game.

824
00:43:44,846 --> 00:43:48,968
So starting with advertising, there it's really critical.

825
00:43:49,048 --> 00:43:52,409
And there's tons and tons of tools.

826
00:43:52,469 --> 00:43:56,010
Almost any ad network that you use is going to expect you to

827
00:43:56,030 --> 00:43:57,151
do A-B testing.

828
00:43:57,431 --> 00:44:00,112
And this is important because the same creatives that work

829
00:44:00,332 --> 00:44:03,773
on congregate.com versus Facebook versus a video ad

830
00:44:03,813 --> 00:44:05,834
network, people are not going to respond to

831
00:44:05,874 --> 00:44:06,534
them the same way.

832
00:44:06,574 --> 00:44:09,075
So you want to have a ton of creatives that are constantly

833
00:44:09,115 --> 00:44:11,316
testing, and this is very important to get

834
00:44:11,956 --> 00:44:12,737
advertising to work.

835
00:44:13,969 --> 00:44:17,951
It's also really important wherever players are converting

836
00:44:18,051 --> 00:44:21,113
to actually play your game, whether it's a landing page

837
00:44:21,433 --> 00:44:23,375
or a store page on a platform.

838
00:44:23,855 --> 00:44:27,897
The problem with this is that outside of Android,

839
00:44:27,917 --> 00:44:29,878
there's not really great test tools.

840
00:44:29,918 --> 00:44:31,399
But you can use things like StoreMaven

841
00:44:31,739 --> 00:44:36,002
and other types of services to sort of fake test those.

842
00:44:36,082 --> 00:44:38,964
And whenever you have a platform that does allow you to test,

843
00:44:39,344 --> 00:44:40,284
make sure that you do it.

844
00:44:41,453 --> 00:44:44,680
It's still pretty easy to test on the initial experience of a player,

845
00:44:44,701 --> 00:44:48,208
you know, getting through tutorials, getting through the first day.

846
00:44:50,733 --> 00:44:54,256
There's no real big gotchas in that.

847
00:44:54,576 --> 00:44:57,238
But there is one thing that's important, which is that

848
00:44:57,418 --> 00:45:00,740
testing on the first day generally doesn't have huge,

849
00:45:01,441 --> 00:45:03,302
show very strong results.

850
00:45:03,862 --> 00:45:06,744
Usually what you're looking for there is how long do

851
00:45:06,784 --> 00:45:07,585
players retain?

852
00:45:07,705 --> 00:45:09,066
How deep do they get into the game?

853
00:45:09,206 --> 00:45:10,306
How much do they play?

854
00:45:10,727 --> 00:45:14,489
And in the end, how fun your core loop is, is going to

855
00:45:14,529 --> 00:45:15,630
determine those things.

856
00:45:15,870 --> 00:45:18,352
And when you're testing the initial experience, you're

857
00:45:18,372 --> 00:45:19,152
really just testing.

858
00:45:19,458 --> 00:45:23,441
that presentation. And the presentation of something has some impact, but doesn't usually

859
00:45:23,461 --> 00:45:30,987
have as much impact as the game itself. Where we've seen more meaningful testing on our

860
00:45:31,047 --> 00:45:34,070
side is in the first few weeks that somebody is in the game.

861
00:45:34,477 --> 00:45:37,019
This is where we've seen good luck with tests, where we're

862
00:45:37,039 --> 00:45:41,343
testing out how we unlock features and good results on

863
00:45:42,023 --> 00:45:43,565
store testing and other things.

864
00:45:43,865 --> 00:45:46,987
This is a sort of a sweet spot for testing in a way that's

865
00:45:47,028 --> 00:45:49,450
meaningful in a game, because players are still new enough

866
00:45:49,490 --> 00:45:53,673
to a game that you haven't kind of wired them into a

867
00:45:53,693 --> 00:45:55,435
particular type of behavior.

868
00:45:56,396 --> 00:45:59,699
But it's deep enough that it can be meaningful, and you can

869
00:46:00,019 --> 00:46:01,600
test really substantial features.

870
00:46:02,975 --> 00:46:07,117
But then once you get to late game, it's pretty difficult.

871
00:46:07,797 --> 00:46:10,078
It's not impossible, but you should tread carefully.

872
00:46:10,638 --> 00:46:12,719
There's a lot of problems with payers talking to each other.

873
00:46:12,799 --> 00:46:16,320
There's a lot of problems with sample sizes,

874
00:46:16,480 --> 00:46:18,341
audience mix, et cetera.

875
00:46:18,381 --> 00:46:21,562
So it's not impossible, but given how much effort testing

876
00:46:21,762 --> 00:46:24,683
is, I wouldn't recommend focusing on that.

877
00:46:27,167 --> 00:46:30,148
So besides that there's a hierarchy of testing, I also

878
00:46:30,208 --> 00:46:33,989
like to think that there's a lifecycle for data in games.

879
00:46:34,569 --> 00:46:42,391
And it kind of follows the stages of the game creation and

880
00:46:42,411 --> 00:46:44,072
the lifecycle of creation of the game.

881
00:46:44,392 --> 00:46:46,913
And that can be loosely split into two sides.

882
00:46:47,153 --> 00:46:50,134
One is the creation, concepting, pre-production,

883
00:46:50,254 --> 00:46:50,694
production.

884
00:46:51,264 --> 00:46:52,446
versus optimization.

885
00:46:52,806 --> 00:46:56,450
And in my view, the optimization phase,

886
00:46:56,530 --> 00:47:00,215
where you're trying to answer the questions of what's

887
00:47:00,275 --> 00:47:02,337
working, what's not working, what's breaking,

888
00:47:02,698 --> 00:47:05,381
it's really crucial for all games, free to play, premium,

889
00:47:05,441 --> 00:47:06,362
whatever you're doing.

890
00:47:07,263 --> 00:47:10,727
Every game can be made better by looking at data.

891
00:47:11,970 --> 00:47:15,553
For any game as a service, that LiveOps looking at data,

892
00:47:15,953 --> 00:47:17,054
it's absolutely critical.

893
00:47:17,635 --> 00:47:21,658
We'll only make games better as long as you don't fall into a

894
00:47:21,698 --> 00:47:22,739
lot of the classic blunders.

895
00:47:23,460 --> 00:47:25,322
Where things get more interesting, from my

896
00:47:25,362 --> 00:47:25,822
perspective, is the game.

897
00:47:26,145 --> 00:47:30,647
perspective and where I don't think I have it figured out at all is on the creation side.

898
00:47:31,247 --> 00:47:34,328
Now, production, I don't think there's really a role for data in it.

899
00:47:34,408 --> 00:47:36,729
You just need to make the game. You're not really answering questions.

900
00:47:36,749 --> 00:47:38,510
You're just trying to get to the fun.

901
00:47:39,270 --> 00:47:43,852
But there's a really big, when you're in concepting and pre-production,

902
00:47:44,453 --> 00:47:47,434
you're asking a really big question, which is, what should we make?

903
00:47:47,914 --> 00:47:51,836
And this is the question always for game companies.

904
00:47:51,916 --> 00:47:55,057
This is deciding the fate of your company again and again.

905
00:47:55,117 --> 00:47:55,698
You're committing.

906
00:47:56,378 --> 00:47:59,660
enormous amounts of resources, you're potentially committing years to a project,

907
00:48:00,100 --> 00:48:04,342
it's what's defining your brand, it's setting you up for both success and

908
00:48:04,382 --> 00:48:09,945
failure, and this is the most important question that you can ask. We've done a

909
00:48:10,005 --> 00:48:14,468
lot of, you know, being a data-driven company, we've tried to pull data into

910
00:48:14,608 --> 00:48:17,389
some of that creation process, and we've had luck with

911
00:48:18,199 --> 00:48:21,061
a particular series of games of collectible card games

912
00:48:21,561 --> 00:48:23,822
that we've made, starting with Tyrant Unleashed, which

913
00:48:23,882 --> 00:48:29,864
is a very hardcore, gritty, sci-fi themed collectible card

914
00:48:29,905 --> 00:48:32,326
game that had really great monetization

915
00:48:32,366 --> 00:48:34,887
and long-term retention, but very high CPIs.

916
00:48:34,947 --> 00:48:36,147
It was very hard to market.

917
00:48:36,447 --> 00:48:37,468
So we looked at that game and said,

918
00:48:37,508 --> 00:48:38,728
we want to make it more marketable.

919
00:48:39,089 --> 00:48:41,750
So we reworked the game.

920
00:48:42,830 --> 00:48:45,672
The team Synapse in Chicago is the one who makes it.

921
00:48:46,512 --> 00:48:49,694
And they did a brightly colored fantasy,

922
00:48:49,814 --> 00:48:53,236
cartoony themed version of it to make it more accessible.

923
00:48:53,596 --> 00:48:54,856
And that did lower the CPIs.

924
00:48:54,917 --> 00:48:56,477
It didn't really make the game more successful,

925
00:48:56,757 --> 00:49:00,680
but it did make progress along those lines.

926
00:49:01,600 --> 00:49:04,302
Then we were able to license from Fox

927
00:49:04,342 --> 00:49:05,642
a bunch of animated IPs,

928
00:49:05,962 --> 00:49:07,743
and were able to create Animation Throwdown,

929
00:49:08,344 --> 00:49:09,644
fundamentally the same game,

930
00:49:09,905 --> 00:49:12,586
but we worked a lot on the accessibility of the early part,

931
00:49:12,866 --> 00:49:14,727
and these characters made the same gameplay.

932
00:49:15,248 --> 00:49:16,669
very, very accessible.

933
00:49:16,929 --> 00:49:18,330
So that was a big success for us.

934
00:49:19,271 --> 00:49:21,833
So then we went to, we were like,

935
00:49:21,893 --> 00:49:25,095
okay, let's test art before we even start making the game.

936
00:49:26,096 --> 00:49:28,738
So again, with Synapse, they were making a game

937
00:49:28,838 --> 00:49:29,798
that was gonna be an idle game,

938
00:49:29,818 --> 00:49:31,800
so we tested a bunch of different creatives

939
00:49:31,860 --> 00:49:32,560
against each other.

940
00:49:33,401 --> 00:49:37,684
Eon Heroes, Relic Raiders, and Castaway Cove.

941
00:49:38,124 --> 00:49:40,666
And the most casual one, Castaway Cove,

942
00:49:40,766 --> 00:49:42,447
had a really good click-through rate,

943
00:49:42,727 --> 00:49:43,908
and we decided to go with that.

944
00:49:45,020 --> 00:49:51,162
But the funny thing happened is that as we got to test

945
00:49:51,202 --> 00:49:54,644
markets, that data didn't hold up particularly well.

946
00:49:55,344 --> 00:49:59,286
We went through three rounds of testing of Castaway Cove,

947
00:49:59,366 --> 00:50:01,707
in each case, really good click-through rates, as you

948
00:50:01,747 --> 00:50:02,307
can see here.

949
00:50:02,788 --> 00:50:05,969
But once we got to test markets and a broader sample,

950
00:50:06,389 --> 00:50:07,490
they really took a nosedive.

951
00:50:07,950 --> 00:50:12,712
And then on top of that, we finally were able to see the

952
00:50:12,752 --> 00:50:14,293
conversion on the store page.

953
00:50:14,703 --> 00:50:16,724
We usually target 30% or higher.

954
00:50:17,105 --> 00:50:18,846
And this one, it was really disappointing.

955
00:50:18,866 --> 00:50:19,787
It was 22%.

956
00:50:21,148 --> 00:50:24,570
And overall, it's not that the CPIs for this game are bad,

957
00:50:24,630 --> 00:50:25,531
but they're pretty average.

958
00:50:25,571 --> 00:50:27,052
And we're really trying to make something

959
00:50:27,092 --> 00:50:28,013
better than average.

960
00:50:28,473 --> 00:50:32,156
Part of it, I think, is that the gameplay and the creative

961
00:50:32,236 --> 00:50:33,917
didn't really work together.

962
00:50:34,038 --> 00:50:36,299
And that conversion piece, which we weren't able to test

963
00:50:36,419 --> 00:50:36,700
earlier,

964
00:50:37,081 --> 00:50:41,268
was important. I also think it's just some of the limitations of testing.

965
00:50:41,849 --> 00:50:44,554
There's probably another five or ten things that we did wrong,

966
00:50:44,834 --> 00:50:47,920
but it shows that you can't just necessarily use science

967
00:50:48,220 --> 00:50:49,282
to figure out what you should make.

968
00:50:51,018 --> 00:50:54,662
The other thing to keep in mind when using data to figure out

969
00:50:54,682 --> 00:50:57,265
what to make is that data maps the known world.

970
00:50:57,706 --> 00:51:03,393
This is a map from 1457 made by a Genoese map maker.

971
00:51:03,413 --> 00:51:07,337
And at the time, it was the best map that had been made in

972
00:51:07,518 --> 00:51:09,560
several thousand years.

973
00:51:10,640 --> 00:51:13,082
It was the first map in a long time that had the relative

974
00:51:13,142 --> 00:51:15,304
proportions of the continents correct.

975
00:51:15,884 --> 00:51:20,388
And if you look at the Mediterranean and anything near

976
00:51:20,448 --> 00:51:22,209
Genoa, it's actually a pretty good map.

977
00:51:22,529 --> 00:51:25,592
But the farther you get out into Africa, into Asia, into

978
00:51:25,612 --> 00:51:28,334
the Baltic, it gets more and more crappy.

979
00:51:28,734 --> 00:51:31,156
And our view of the world is a little bit like that.

980
00:51:31,836 --> 00:51:35,019
And even more, there was a huge amount of the world that

981
00:51:35,039 --> 00:51:37,861
was completely unknown to that Genoese map maker.

982
00:51:38,220 --> 00:51:39,361
And that's really important.

983
00:51:39,521 --> 00:51:41,322
And games and data are like that.

984
00:51:42,762 --> 00:51:45,744
If you're using data to decide what you're going to make, that

985
00:51:45,764 --> 00:51:47,765
data is always going to tell you to make a slightly better

986
00:51:47,825 --> 00:51:49,706
version of something that was already a success.

987
00:51:49,786 --> 00:51:54,108
So Madden every year for 20 or 30 years.

988
00:51:54,508 --> 00:51:56,489
But it's not going to tell you to make something like Journey,

989
00:51:56,549 --> 00:51:58,790
which is very different from anything that's been made

990
00:51:58,830 --> 00:52:01,251
before and is a wonderful experience.

991
00:52:03,223 --> 00:52:05,244
I don't think there's a particularly right answer.

992
00:52:05,264 --> 00:52:07,605
Again, I like framework.

993
00:52:07,705 --> 00:52:11,647
So what I've put together is kind of from the left side,

994
00:52:11,907 --> 00:52:16,329
familiarity, to the right side, you have innovation.

995
00:52:16,349 --> 00:52:19,650
And from the bottom, you have unknown newcomer.

996
00:52:20,130 --> 00:52:22,191
to at the top, established incumbent.

997
00:52:22,852 --> 00:52:27,473
Most game developer, oh sorry, EA Sports is a good example

998
00:52:27,493 --> 00:52:29,594
of what you would find in the top left

999
00:52:30,655 --> 00:52:34,436
because it's a huge company making a familiar game

1000
00:52:34,556 --> 00:52:36,997
of a familiar game again and again and again.

